{
  "title": "2022-11-14",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "df613cbaa3989f25",
      "text": "HERRMANN, Ulrike, 2022. Raus aus der Wachstumsfalle. Blätter für deutsche und internationale Politik. Online. 2022. No. 10, p. 57–66. [https://www.blaetter.de/ausgabe/2022/oktober/raus-aus-der-wachstumsfalle page]\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a7ea2d6a122b91b6",
      "text": "[[Capitalism]] has undoubtedly been a historical advance, but unfortunately it has a fundamental weakness: it not only generates growth, but it must also grow in order to be stable. Without constant expansion, capitalism collapses. In a finite world, however, you cannot grow infinitely. And yet the industrialized countries act as if they could consume several planets. As is well known, however, there is only one earth."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5486a0b373bdf0e8",
      "text": "The next epoch will therefore have to be a \"survival economy\" that overcomes capitalism. In the climate debate, it is always suggested that we already have the solution and that only the political will is lacking. But in fact, so far there is no concept of how to end capitalism peacefully. There are only arguments about non-solutions. So far, governments are betting that they can somehow reconcile the economy and climate protection. The typical buzzwords are \"Green New Deal\" or \"decoupling\" growth and energy. The great hope is that the entire economy could be converted to green power – whether transport, industry or heating."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c82fdc223058de4c",
      "text": "However, this \"green growth\" is an illusion, because green electricity will not be enough. This statement may come as a surprise at first, after all, the sun sends 5,000 times more energy to the earth than the eight billion people would need if they were all to enjoy the standard of living of Europeans. So there is no lack of physical energy, but as we know, solar energy must first be captured. Solar panels and wind turbines, however, only provide electricity when the sun is shining and the wind is blowing. To provide for lulls and darkness, energy must be stored – and this intermediate step is so costly that green power will remain scarce. If green energy is to last, the only option is \"green shrinking\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9b4c85d66638551d",
      "text": "It is not a new idea that permanent growth has no future. Many climate activists have long been convinced that nature can only survive if capitalism ends. So they have coined the catchy slogan: \"system change, not climate change.\" Nor is there any shortage of visions of what an ecological circular economy might look like, in which only as much is consumed as can be recycled. Keywords include the barter economy, the common good economy, cutting consumption, reduced working hours and an unconditional basic income."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d5c088efa642e5ea",
      "text": "But how can an ecological circular economy be achieved? That remains unclear, because the vision is for the most part confused with the path. The goal is supposed to be the transition at the same time. It is rarely asked how to actually exit from a constantly growing capitalism without creating a severe economic crisis and sending millions of people into unemployment. The bridge from the dynamic present to a static future is missing."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "51cdaf85f4d331a4",
      "text": "Many climate activists feel that the departure from capitalism will be difficult. Greta Thunberg was recently asked by a supporter what the future system should look like. \"I don't know,\" she replied, \"It hasn't been invented yet.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "801a97ea387b54df",
      "text": "To imagine \"green shrinkage,\" it helps to think from the end. If green electricity remains scarce, air travel and private cars will no longer be possible. Banks will also become largely redundant, because loans can only be repaid if the economy grows. In a carbon-neutral economy, no one would go hungry – but millions of workers would have to change their jobs. For example, many more workers would be needed in agriculture and also in the forests to mitigate the effects of climate change."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4d67982e688016b1",
      "text": "This view of the future may seem radical, but it is literally \"without alternative. If we do not reduce the emitted greenhouse gases to net zero, we will enter a \"hot period\" that will ensure all by itself that the economy shrinks. In this climate chaos, it would probably come to a fight of all against all, which our democracy would not survive."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "59ef0284eb376d2f",
      "text": "# Model Great Britain 1939"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8712d30f3505912e",
      "text": "However, some Germans also wonder whether it makes sense at all to think about climate protection on a national level. They fear that other countries might even take advantage if we reduce our greenhouse gases. For example, economist Hans Werner Sinn writes, \"Whether you think about coal, oil or natural gas, if Germany buys and burns less, then the Chinese can just buy and burn more.\" This mistrust is understandable, but it fails to recognize that almost all other countries are suffering from the climate catastrophe to an even greater extent than Germany. It is in their own interest to reduce greenhouse gases as well."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0ea8ced2cf0c1ba2",
      "text": "The core error of market-oriented economists is that they think green energy is a normal product that can be multiplied at will as demand increases. So they believe that only \"price signals\" would be needed to force the expansion of wind turbines and solar panels. The idea is that if CO2 taxes are high enough, fossil energy will become so expensive that all companies and households will enthusiastically switch to green energy. But green energy cannot be increased at will – it will remain scarce, if only for physical and technical reasons. Green technology not only consumes steel, concrete and aluminum, which have been in sufficient supply up to now, but also rather scarce minerals. These include lithium, nickel, copper, cobalt, manganese, graphite and rare earths such as neodymium. Just for comparison: a conventional car needs 35 kilos of these raw materials, while an e-car needs around 210 kilos – six times as much. Wind turbines don't turn on their own either. More than 10,000 kilograms of minerals are needed per megawatt of installed power, and when the rotors are in the sea, the figure is as high as 15,000 kilograms. Solar panels do not require quite as many raw materials, but they also come to 7,000 kilos. Conventional power plants are much more economical: if coal is burned, 2500 kilos of minerals are needed per megawatt; with gas, it's only 1200 kilos. The demand for minerals will therefore explode if the entire world wants to operate on a climate-neutral basis. The International Energy Agency predicts that demand for copper will more than double by 2040, while that for lithium will increase 42-fold, graphite 25-fold, cobalt 21-fold, nickel 19-fold and rare earths seven-fold. But economists do not deal with these very concrete questions; they remain in their theoretical world of prices."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2e27efb554bb5890",
      "text": "The debate has become deadlocked, with two camps irreconcilably opposed: Most politicians, climate researchers and economists hope for \"green growth,\" although green energy is unlikely to be enough. Conversely, the growth critics therefore demand that income and consumption must fall. But they lack a plan for how to avoid a severe economic crisis in the process, plunging millions of people into poverty and despair."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "38daf4c8a28406fb",
      "text": "# Shrink without creating chaos"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5e10b7d060d14d08",
      "text": "So we are looking for an idea on how to shrink the economy without causing chaos. Fortunately, history offers a model for this. The British wartime economy, of all things, is a good example of how to strive for a climate-neutral world in an orderly manner."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7259834521db6675",
      "text": "To avoid possible misunderstandings, not every wartime economy is suitable as a model. Only the British war economy from 1939 onward is described here. It was by no means the only war economy that has ever existed in world history. At the moment, Putin's brutal attack on Ukraine shows that every military conflict has dramatic consequences for the economy as well. Moreover, in a single war, there can be multiple models of how the economy is reshaped. In World War II, not only the British and Americans, but also Hitler and Stalin each had their own forms of a war economy. Not every war economy is therefore suitable as an analogy for how an ecological transformation could be designed."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "97d9b0f8cdc2b119",
      "text": "In 1939, the British were faced with a monstrous challenge: they had not seen the Second World War coming and now had to gear their economy to the military in the shortest possible time without starving the population. Almost overnight, a planned economy was created that worked remarkably well. Factories remained in private hands, but the state controlled production - and organized the distribution of scarce goods. There was rationing, but there were no shortages. The British thus invented a private and democratic planned economy that had nothing to do with the dysfunctional socialism in the Soviet Union."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f1f50e3704acd5e0",
      "text": "# The war as a metaphor - and motivation for maximum effort"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c06b64894180461b",
      "text": "Of course, it would be ludicrous to simply copy the measures taken back then – after all, we are living almost a century later and are not at war with the climate either. But there are some parallels that are very instructive for a sustainable future. For in the case of the British wartime economy from 1939 onward, several factors come together to make it interesting as a stimulus. First, the British lived in a democracy; their Prime Minister Churchill was freely elected. An \"eco-dictatorship\" is rightly feared, but as the British proved, democracies are also capable of decisive action. Second, the British were not waging a war of aggression, but had to defend themselves against Hitler. They were in an involuntary emergency situation, which, moreover, was recognized belatedly. For a long time, the British had still hoped that they could pacify Hitler through \"appeasement\" and keep him from going to war. We are experiencing climate change in a similar way today. Its dramatic nature was only understood with a delay, but now forces us to act. Third, the British had to sharply downsize their normal economy in a very short time to free up capacity in factories to produce military goods. There is a lesson to be learned from all this about how to organize a shrinking economy."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3a817a23bd6237cc",
      "text": "Critics of growth are often accused of taking great pleasure in tormenting their fellow human beings. \"Paternalism is fun for those who come up with the bans,\" complains \"Bild\" journalist Nena Schink, who fears that Germany could \"mutate into a nation of bans. Unfortunately, it won't work without bans. Our way of life can only be ecological if not everyone consumes unlimitedly at all times. The analogy to World War II is therefore apt: it makes clear that it costs sacrifices to build an ecological circular economy. Only renunciation ensures survival - as in war."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a413ec125027d7ca",
      "text": "It is also not uncommon to speak of \"war\" as soon as a major problem needs to be solved. Wars have been declared against poverty, drugs and cancer. However, the word \"war\" is used here only as a metaphor and is intended to emphasize that maximum effort is required. It was also common during the Corona pandemic to draw military comparisons. U.S. President Trump - after long downplaying the virus - said in a press conference, \"We're at war, and we're fighting an invisible enemy.\" French President Macron also saw himself at war, requiring \"general mobilization,\" while Britain's Queen Elizabeth II spoke of caregivers \"on the front lines.\" This time, the analogies to World War II were literal, and some states even reactivated wartime ordinances. Trump, for example, brought back the \"Defense Production Act,\" which had been enacted in 1950 during the Korean War to force the car company General Motors to produce ventilators. Just as tanks had once been produced for battle, masks and vaccines were now considered \"weapons against the virus.\" And, as in wartime, the state took all the important decisions: within days, schools and restaurants were closed, employees were sent to the home office, huge rescue packages were put together and borders were partially sealed off. Money was no longer an issue; the only thing that mattered was \"victory\" against the pandemic. This showed that the state can act when it wants to."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "65178ea639ba3609",
      "text": "# The state can act if it wants to"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f2f9402b83c99c8a",
      "text": "This fact has not escaped the attention of climate activists: They also tend to compare the fight against the climate crisis with the Second World War. As early as 2018, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) wanted a global \"mobilization,\" and Nobel Prize-winning economist Joseph Stiglitz also promotes this idea. Climate activists are particularly excited by how quickly the Allies managed to produce the necessary arsenals of weapons to defeat Germany and its allies back then. Now, wind turbines, solar panels and electric cars are to be produced just as quickly."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "145b83e98d64e9f8",
      "text": "Most authors, however, are not so much interested in Great Britain as in the USA, because huge arms factories were built there from nothing after the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor in December 1941. Among other things, the Americans built an aircraft factory in Michigan in just six months that produced 24 B24 bombers a day, although each plane required 1,225,000 parts and 313,237 rivets. Similarly impressive was U.S. production of the standardized \"Liberty\" freighters. These ships were intended to compensate for losses incurred by German U-boats in the Atlantic. Initially, it took eight months to produce a single freighter, which consisted of 250,000 parts. In the end, one ship was built every five days. At the same time, existing factories were simply repurposed: Heating companies made helmets, underwear became camouflage nets, calculating machines turned into guns, and vacuum cleaner bags found themselves in gas masks. The fabrics for car seats became parachutes, while car companies built machine guns and cannons, fighter planes and tanks. Between 1942 and 1945, the U.S. government spent more money than it had used in total from 1789 to 1941. During the war years, the U.S. produced 87,000 naval ships, 300,000 aircraft, 100,000 armored vehicles and tanks, and 44 billion rounds of ammunition. Even U.S. President Roosevelt marveled at this \"miracle of production.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4943fcd00294add2",
      "text": "# Pain-free ecological?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f3d768fdcaad01ad",
      "text": "This gigantic material battle had boosted growth powerfully at the time, and many climate activists unfold similarly optimistic visions when it comes to the future. U.S. activist Bill McKibben, for example, enthuses, \"Stopping climate change would generate enormous social and economic benefits, just like World War II did.\" Philippine economist Laurence Delina also wants to avoid \"paralyzing pessimism\" and believes he has found the right tool in the war economy to develop \"highly optimistic strategies\" so that climate change mitigation \"can become one of the greatest opportunities for social, technical, political, economic, and cultural change.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9b866c4d315b5034",
      "text": "Among climate activists, the U.S. war economy is also popular because it was largely painless. The Americans did have to cut back a bit during the war, as companies no longer manufactured cars or nylon pantyhose, but instead produced tanks and parachute silk. But overall, the sacrifices were limited. There was still more than one kilo of meat per person and week - which is exactly the amount that Germans eat today on a weekly average. The actual rearmament was also easily financed. Although the military consumed up to 42 percent of economic output, the overall economy expanded much faster. In the U.S., it grew by 90.5 percent overall, and in Canada it doubled by more than 100 percent. North Americans got richer in the war."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b606615918d3acb6",
      "text": "But precisely because the growth in the U.S. at that time was so incredible, copying the war economy of the North Americans cannot be the green future. The green energy would never be enough to produce this flood of materials. Of course, the maximum we have to invest in is wind turbines, solar panels, heat pumps, electrolysers, power grids, railroad tracks or batteries – in that respect, the comparison with the American mobilization in World War II is apt. But rapid and exorbitant growth must not result. The British wartime economy is therefore better suited to provide a model for the future. For in the United Kingdom, civilian production actually had to shrink sharply to free up capacity for the military. The war took up about 50 percent of British economic output – which hardly expanded at all during this period. From 1939 to 1945, overall growth reached only 27 percent. Although the British were able to import weapons and goods from North America and the Commonwealth as well, these were nowhere near enough to maintain peacetime living standards. The war was taking its toll."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "719a90c3fea5dc02",
      "text": "The British had underestimated Hitler for a long time because they did not want to fight again under any circumstances. \"Never again\" was the motto because the First World War had been so terrible. Between 1914 and 1918, more than 16.5 million people had died, including 723,000 Britons and another 230,000 soldiers from the British Commonwealth. In addition, the costs of war were daunting: The Great Depression had left severe damage in its wake, and to relieve the burden on the national budget, British defense spending had been cut by a quarter by 1934."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0c76e7305f3d1fe5",
      "text": "The British secret services were well informed about Hitler's rearmament, but for a long time the government reassured itself that the Germans only wanted to restore their \"national unity\". It was not until the \"Sudeten Crisis\" that the British were startled, when Hitler ultimatley demanded in 1938 that the Sudetenland be annexed to the German Reich. Nevertheless, the British agreed to the \"Munich Agreement\" in September 1938. The Germans were allowed to occupy the Sudetenland, while Hitler promised to respect the sovereignty of the rest of Czechoslovakia. That this was a sham was not understood by most British until March 15, 1939, when German tanks rolled into Prague."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a795570c44547929",
      "text": "In retrospect, it seems naïve that British Prime Minister Chamberlain was convinced for a long time that \"Herr Hitler's aims were absolutely limited\" and that he was \"telling the truth\" when he asserted that he did not want to bring the Czechs \"home to the Reich\". But at that time, in fact, it hardly seemed conceivable that Hitler would want to start another world war. For it was clear that he would lose this war. The German Reich was simply too poor to subjugate all of Europe. The British, on the other hand, were a military superpower at the time. They possessed the largest fleet and the largest aircraft production in the world. The army was small, but fully motorized. No British soldier walked on foot; they all sat in armored cars. In September 1940, therefore, the British military leadership still believed that victory could be expected as early as 1942. Instead, it turned out to be five agonizingly long years."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7c2be59ac441a5a9",
      "text": "# From market to private planned economy"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "29a0a6d0f0cac806",
      "text": "When the Second World War began, the intention was to avoid the mistakes of the First as far as possible. From 1914 onward, decisions had been made for the most part on an ad hoc basis and it was not until late that it was realized that an all-out war required comprehensive planning. In 1939, therefore, the British did not waste any more precious time, but immediately organized a kind of \"private planned economy\". The state specified what was to be produced - but the companies remained the property of their owners. Companies, craft businesses, restaurants or stores were not nationalized, but could continue to decide for themselves how to run their businesses."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "835082cba26a2f5d",
      "text": "The British planned economy thus differed fundamentally from the socialism practiced at the same time under Stalin in the Soviet Union. In this \"centrally planned economy of the Soviet type,\" all enterprises were state-owned, and the way in which the factories produced their goods was regulated down to the last screw. The British government, on the other hand, directed the factories indirectly - by allocating raw materials, credit and labor. Above all, employees were in such short supply that companies could only produce if they were allocated employees: The \"manpower budget\" became the government's central control instrument."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a3eba887871b2714",
      "text": "The planning authorities themselves also needed a lot of manpower. The new Ministry of Food alone employed 3,500 people in April 1940, and 39,000 in 1943. Nevertheless, these huge bureaucracies did not lead a life of their own, far removed from everyday life, because the authorities were interspersed with experts and businessmen. Economists, scientists, engineers, and entrepreneurs were specifically hired. Initially, however, the necessary figures were lacking to be able to plan at all. National accounts did not yet exist. No one could say how many weapons, airplanes and tanks could be produced without the population having to starve."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e347b5a1fe079a80",
      "text": "# The invention of GDP"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c2bbdd4ebf17cb3f",
      "text": "To fill these gaps in knowledge, gross domestic product (GDP) was invented as a measure at the time. It was, if you will, a British weapon of war. Its success was so resounding that it was later adopted by almost all countries worldwide: GDP has become the most important statistical variable in economics because it measures economic performance and thus growth. Thanks to GDP, it was now possible to accurately estimate that 66 percent of British industrial capacity was needed to arm the military, leaving hardly any goods for the civilian population. The need was far greater than in peacetime because German bombs destroyed more than a million British homes. In addition, food supplies had to be cut because Britain was not self-sufficient and was dependent on imports for 70 percent of its food. These imports absolutely had to fall because ships were now needed to bring in weapons and military raw materials from overseas. Foodstuffs cost valuable space."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "df61372d043c35b7",
      "text": "It was calculated exactly how many calories could be imported with which foodstuff. The result was that 1,000 cubic feet of shipping space could carry 83,000 sugar calories, over 100,000 fat calories and 56,000 grain calories – but only 12,000 calories if fresh eggs were to be shipped. So these were eliminated and dried egg powder was invented instead. The British did not starve in the Second World War, because per capita and day there were 2800 calories.That was enough: Today health insurance companies advise that men should eat a maximum of 2400 calories. For women, it is even only 1900 calories. But quantity does not equal quality. Meat, cheese, fat, sugar, tea and soap were in such short supply that they had to be rationed. However, there was no real shortage even of these rare goods. There was still enough for at least 540 grams of meat per week; military personnel even received an impressive 1.2 kilos. Only milk and eggs were almost never available for normal adults, but were reserved for children, pregnant women and nursing mothers. Potatoes, flour and bread were not rationed. Fish, poultry, game, offal, vegetables and fruits were also not limited. This was because they were either perishable, available only at certain times, or not sufficiently available to guarantee rations for all.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a7cff4e51a127120",
      "text": "Scarce, of course, were extras such as canned food, cookies, chocolate, candy or dried fruit. There was a points system for them. Each customer could decide individually for which goods he wanted to use his points. Depending on the total supply, the government changed the number of points needed for a particular product. This point system also applied to furniture and clothes. To save materials and labor, they were standardized so that chairs or plates always looked the same. There were also strict rules for clothes, so that no unnecessary ornaments were sewn on. For example, a woman's dress could only have a maximum of two pockets and five buttons. Quantity and price controls were immensely popular in Britain. As the British government noted as early as 1941, the rationing program was \"one of the greatest successes on the home front.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "372d68c931c40963",
      "text": "# The blessing of state-imposed egalitarianism"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a9ab61631ce35fc2",
      "text": "The state-imposed egalitarianism proved to be a blessing: During the war, of all times, the lower classes were better fed than ever before. In peacetime, one-third of the British had not received enough calories, and another 20 percent were at least partially malnourished. Now, in the midst of war, the population was healthier than ever, with \"the fitness of babies and schoolchildren standing out particularly.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3829e1b4ab8dcd53",
      "text": "The rationing programs were so popular because every Briton got exactly the same thing. However, it was only half the truth that wealth no longer mattered at all. After all, the elites had the money they needed to buy non-rationed goods such as fish or game, and could also go to expensive restaurants. But these injustices were later forgotten. In retrospect, the war was glorified as a \"time of public spirit,\" \"in which class and status differences faded and the nameless was as important as the prince.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "08dfa6d853496a70",
      "text": "Consumption fell by a third at that time - and in a very short time. This enormous cutback and restructuring makes the British wartime economy a fascinating model for today: German consumption must fall similarly drastically if the climate is to be saved."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "44b1c6214806b0b5",
      "text": "However, today no one has to fear that there would again be only potatoes, bread and two dresses per year. It would not be that bleak. In the past 80 years, the German economy has grown tenfold in real terms. Even if only half of this enormous prosperity remained, we would still be as rich as we were in 1978. Those who were around at that time remember: \"Star Wars\" filled the movie theaters, and Argentina became soccer world champion. Kids played with Bonanza wheels and Slime. Life felt little different than it does today, but it was a bit more leisurely. Instead of jetting off to Mallorca several times for a long weekend, people drove their own cars to Italy once a year for three weeks. In a carbon-neutral world, you'd be traveling by train, but vacations would still be a given."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e395112b12047b79",
      "text": "# The entry into the circular economy"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "42c00931bef282e0",
      "text": "Such a model could be the entry point to a true circular economy. The \"share economy\" has already developed beguiling visions of what a comfortable life could look like that consumes only as much as can be recycled. The goal is clear, only the path is missing. So far, there is no plan for how to end the dynamic growth of capitalism without threatening a severe economic crisis. The British wartime economy could provide such a model: It shows how a private planned economy can shrink civilian production in an orderly manner - and how scarce goods can then be rationed so that social peace is maintained."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bd4c8ae7e001d5dc",
      "text": "Certainly, nowadays planning and rationing have a bad reputation. Anyone who doesn't rely on the \"free market\" is accused of trying to bully his fellow man. In an interview, even the Green Party's Anton Hofreiter expressed his outrage: \"Should people be given a quota for how much they can drive? Should there be ration coupons for meat? That is absurd. We are in a free society, fortunately there are no such instruments.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "76d5055853c44b06",
      "text": "Like Hofreiter, many people believe that the \"free market\" and state control are opposites that are absolutely mutually exclusive. But that is a mistake. Even under capitalism, there has always been planning - by companies and by governments. The British demonstrated during World War II how a government can effectively steer to radically transform the economy. However, the British wartime economy could only work so well because it did not introduce anything radically new, but only radicalized what was already inherent in capitalism. For even if market radicals like to suppress it: Even in normal times, the state plays a supporting role. Therefore, it would be possible at any time to switch back to a kind of war economy in order to save the climate. True to the motto: learning from the experience of capitalism means learning to win."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7b81349aeb642353",
      "text": "The article is based on \"The End of Capitalism: Why Growth and Climate Protection Are Incompatible - and How We Will Live in the Future,\" (Das Ende des Kapitalismus: Warum Wachstum und Klimaschutz nicht vereinbar sind – und wie wir in Zukunft leben werden) the author's latest book, which has just been published by Kiepenheuer & Witsch."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4b1cbcac68e25ad6",
      "text": "Topics: Ecology, History, Neoliberalism"
    },
