      "type": "edit",
      "id": "7259834521db6675",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "7259834521db6675",
        "text": "Um möglichen Missverständnissen vorzubeugen: Nicht jede Kriegswirtschaft eignet sich als Vorbild. Hier wird nur die britische Kriegswirtschaft ab 1939 geschildert. Sie war keineswegs die einzige Kriegswirtschaft, die es in der Weltgeschichte je gegeben hat. Momentan zeigt Putins brutaler Angriff auf die Ukraine, dass jede militärische Auseinandersetzung dramatische Folgen auch für die Wirtschaft hat. Zudem kann es in einem einzigen Krieg gleich mehrere Modelle geben, wie die Ökonomie umgestaltet wird. Im Zweiten Weltkrieg hatten nicht nur die Briten und Amerikaner, sondern auch Hitler und Stalin ihre je eigenen Formen einer Kriegswirtschaft. Nicht jede Kriegswirtschaft eignet sich also als Analogie, wie sich eine ökologische Transformation gestalten ließe."
      },
      "date": 1668426760463
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "7259834521db6675",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "7259834521db6675",
        "text": "To avoid possible misunderstandings, not every wartime economy is suitable as a model. Only the British war economy from 1939 onward is described here. It was by no means the only war economy that has ever existed in world history. At the moment, Putin's brutal attack on Ukraine shows that every military conflict has dramatic consequences for the economy as well. Moreover, in a single war, there can be multiple models of how the economy is reshaped. In World War II, not only the British and Americans, but also Hitler and Stalin each had their own forms of a war economy. Not every war economy is therefore suitable as an analogy for how an ecological transformation could be designed."
      },
      "date": 1668426765145
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "97d9b0f8cdc2b119",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "97d9b0f8cdc2b119",
        "text": "In 1939, the British were faced with a monstrous challenge: they had not seen the Second World War coming and now had to gear their economy to the military in the shortest possible time without starving the population. Almost overnight, a planned economy was created that worked remarkably well. Factories remained in private hands, but the state controlled production - and organized the distribution of scarce goods. There was rationing, but there were no shortages. The British thus invented a private and democratic planned economy that had nothing to do with the dysfunctional socialism in the Soviet Union."
      },
      "after": "7259834521db6675",
      "date": 1668426778331
    },
