      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "145b83e98d64e9f8",
        "text": "Most authors, however, are not so much interested in Great Britain as in the USA, because huge arms factories were built there from nothing after the Japanese attacked Pearl Harbor in December 1941. Among other things, the Americans built an aircraft factory in Michigan in just six months that produced 24 B24 bombers a day, although each plane required 1,225,000 parts and 313,237 rivets.Similarly impressive was U.S. production of the standardized \"Liberty\" freighters. These ships were intended to compensate for losses incurred by German U-boats in the Atlantic. Initially, it took eight months to produce a single freighter, which consisted of 250,000 parts. In the end, one ship was built every five days. At the same time, existing factories were simply repurposed: Heating companies made helmets, underwear became camouflage nets, calculating machines turned into guns, and vacuum cleaner bags found themselves in gas masks. The fabrics for car seats became parachutes, while car companies built machine guns and cannons, fighter planes and tanks. Between 1942 and 1945, the U.S. government spent more money than it had used in total from 1789 to 1941. During the war years, the U.S. produced 87,000 naval ships, 300,000 aircraft, 100,000 armored vehicles and tanks, and 44 billion rounds of ammunition. Even U.S. President Roosevelt marveled at this \"miracle of production.\""
