        "id": "719a90c3fea5dc02",
        "text": "The British had underestimated Hitler for a long time because they did not want to fight again under any circumstances. \"Never again\" was the motto because the First World War had been so terrible. Between 1914 and 1918, more than 16.5 million people had died, including 723,000 Britons and another 230,000 soldiers from the British Commonwealth. In addition, the costs of war were daunting: The Great Depression had left severe damage in its wake, and to relieve the burden on the national budget, British defense spending had been cut by a quarter by 1934."
