    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "e347b5a1fe079a80",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "e347b5a1fe079a80",
        "text": "# The invention of GDP"
      },
      "date": 1668427176775
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "c2bbdd4ebf17cb3f"
      },
      "id": "c2bbdd4ebf17cb3f",
      "type": "add",
      "after": "e347b5a1fe079a80",
      "date": 1668427186182
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "c2bbdd4ebf17cb3f",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "c2bbdd4ebf17cb3f",
        "text": "To fill these gaps in knowledge, gross domestic product (GDP) was invented as a measure at the time. It was, if you will, a British weapon of war. Its success was so resounding that it was later adopted by almost all countries worldwide: GDP has become the most important statistical variable in economics because it measures economic performance and thus growth. Thanks to GDP, it was now possible to accurately estimate that 66 percent of British industrial capacity was needed to arm the military, leaving hardly any goods for the civilian population. The need was far greater than in peacetime because German bombs destroyed more than a million British homes. In addition, food supplies had to be cut because Britain was not self-sufficient and was dependent on imports for 70 percent of its food. These imports absolutely had to fall because ships were now needed to bring in weapons and military raw materials from overseas. Foodstuffs cost valuable space."
      },
      "date": 1668427187042
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "df61372d043c35b7"
      },
      "id": "df61372d043c35b7",
      "type": "add",
      "after": "c2bbdd4ebf17cb3f",
      "date": 1668427199449
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "df61372d043c35b7",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "df61372d043c35b7",
        "text": "It was calculated exactly how many calories could be imported with which foodstuff. The result was that 1,000 cubic feet of shipping space could carry 83,000 sugar calories, over 100,000 fat calories and 56,000 grain calories - but only 12,000 calories if fresh eggs were to be shipped. So these were eliminated and dried egg powder was invented instead. The British did not starve in the Second World War, because per capita and day there were 2800 calories.That was enough: Today health insurance companies advise that men should eat a maximum of 2400 calories. For women, it is even only 1900 calories. But quantity does not equal quality. Meat, cheese, fat, sugar, tea and soap were in such short supply that they had to be rationed. However, there was no real shortage even of these rare goods. There was still enough for at least 540 grams of meat per week; military personnel even received an impressive 1.2 kilos. Only milk and eggs were almost never available for normal adults, but were reserved for children, pregnant women and nursing mothers. Potatoes, flour and bread were not rationed. Fish, poultry, game, offal, vegetables and fruits were also not limited. This was because they were either perishable, available only at certain times, or not sufficiently available to guarantee rations for all.\n\n"
      },
      "date": 1668427200313
