    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "76d5055853c44b06",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "76d5055853c44b06",
        "text": "Like Hofreiter, many people believe that the \"free market\" and state control are opposites that are absolutely mutually exclusive. But that is a mistake. Even under capitalism, there has always been planning - by companies and by governments. The British demonstrated during World War II how a government can effectively steer to radically transform the economy. However, the British wartime economy could only work so well because it did not introduce anything radically new, but only radicalized what was already inherent in capitalism. For even if market radicals like to suppress it: Even in normal times, the state plays a supporting role. Therefore, it would be possible at any time to switch back to a kind of war economy in order to save the climate. True to the motto: learning from the experience of capitalism means learning to win."
